<p><b>Anamorphic widescreen</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Videography" title="Videography">videographic</a> technique utilizing rectangular (wide) pixels to store a <a href="/wiki/Widescreen" title="Widescreen">widescreen</a> image to standard <a href="/wiki/4:3" title="4:3" class="mw-redirect">4:3</a> <a href="/wiki/Aspect_ratio_(image)" title="Aspect ratio (image)">aspect ratio</a>. In its current definition as a <a href="/wiki/Video" title="Video">video</a> term, it originally was devised for widescreen <a href="/wiki/16:9" title="16:9" class="mw-redirect">16:9</a> aspect ratio television sets; however, it has been used in regular film <a href="/wiki/Movies" title="Movies" class="mw-redirect">movies</a> for decades.</p>
